Republican strategy of resistance to re-election of Obama
The Republican leaders justified their policies with the need to fight counterfeiting in the elections.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of electoral falsification in the United States are more rare than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is for sure: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon took on a new dimension after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were passed in 2011 alone.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to register an elector on the day of the declaration of will and deprive citizens of the right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana became the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to spread the practice to other states.
For the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to present photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the age required to vote, do not have an identity card with a photo issued by the government body of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affecting young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID card issued by their educational institution in several states.
But the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, which vote mainly for Republicans, to use the credentials issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship for voting.
This is the first time such a requirement has been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at limiting the voting of Latin Americans.
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on the day of voting in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those wishing to register.
This restriction did not go without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, a campaign to register voters helped list about 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a 17 per cent drop in new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African Americans, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state’s total electorate.
The same thing happened with Latin Americans as well.
Representing only 11% of voters, they made up 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike the whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, only 46% of those who voted were early.
Of course, Democrats and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most ambiguous laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This has partially limited the negative effects.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring a photo ID.
However, the new rules that have entered into force will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Democrat critics condemn the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing in them an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electorate to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Screening for prostate cancer: to pass a test or not?
