Another study, this time a European one, found different levels of mortality in those patients who underwent screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, after 12 years of observation, that metastases were 30-40% more likely to occur in those who did not undergo screening.
Therefore, I would recommend taking a test starting at age 50, or at age 40, if one of the immediate relatives had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision as soon as the cancer is detected.
Cancer can be both aggressive and slow-moving.
The patient needs to explain the degree of risk of his cancer, offering him possible options, without the mandatory treatment of prostate cancer, which does not pose a risk to life in the long term, and making a choice, in these cases, in favor of active monitoring of the disease.
