The Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, a report that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused a real stir — and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much or little.
In addition, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted within the Standard Model—our best, or at least “least imperfect,” description of the nature and behavior of matter—but which has not previously been detected experimentally.
But physicists are not entirely sure that this is the Higgs boson.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it is very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although for complete certainty some data is not yet enough.
Let’s imagine, however, that this is about the Higgs boson, because the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what that means.
There is one absolutely inevitable law in this world that two things cannot end up in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will harm yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that there is also one law of this nature: the Pauli exception principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" of their common characteristics, is the "state" of the
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens, called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
In the other, there are bosons, a disgusting gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything – at least this principle, which means that they can be quietly in the same place at the same time.
As the site (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory reports, these bosons, in turn, are divided into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of force", by means of which the main forces of nature are distributed and to which in some way the bosons belong.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it’s because of one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or “particle of light,” which is the “courier” of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle that has an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disrupts” the electromagnetic field in that particular place, about like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and, therefore, one of the bosons of "power transmitters".
A more stable field.
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference being that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken."
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very and very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the one exploited in the CERN – the Big Hadron Collider, which is a 27-kilometer-diameter ring! – is needed to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never be kept in the refrigerator.
Likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like the photon, by the way) do not.
So, what "can" all these studies bring, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to sense the discrepancy between the results of observations and the forecasts of the SM.
In addition, some of them are passionately eager for such a discrepancy to be discovered, since the slightest discrepancy can open the door to the "new physics" and close some of the holes of the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
But no such differences have yet been found in the CERN.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the everyday life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it does not exist.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell’s laboratories could not even guess what revolution their work would bring.
They predicted their applications in science, but no more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at the Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered a "laboratory gauge".
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same Billiard Boyle during his optical studies in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not its original purpose at all, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die... <0x7C> "Debt"
A delicate end-of-life issue was recently discussed in the Commission for a Decent Death in Quebec.
The debate is expected to resume soon, and a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
"Debt" tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. still lived alone in his apartment in Monterrey.
Prostate cancer, which destroyed him from the inside, gave him a two-year delay.
"I was given five years, I lived seven," he says, lying in bed between life and death in Victor-Gadbu's palliative care shelter in White, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, it's impossible to prepare for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet on your own and even eating on your own.
Sitting at the table where there is an appetizing lunch, he surrenders and agrees to be helped to eat.
He is cheerful, even able to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bathroom.
Courage before ordinary death.
“My greatest desire to be cured of diarrhea is humiliating,” he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for the disease.
"In our lifetimes, we are taught that a man should urinate while standing," says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Viktor-Gadboy shelter.
Regressing to the condition of a child is an unbearable humiliation for some.
“It all depends on a person’s ability to accept decay,” he says.
Since, in the opinion of many people engaged in palliative care, important events occur at the height of this decline.
Patients who are admitted to Victor-Gadboi’s palliative care facility are all cancer patients.
The prognosis gives them a maximum of three months to live.
At this stage, a team of doctors and nurses no longer provide assistance, called “medical.”
Ms. A., 89 years old, is most afraid to die "in consciousness from suffocation".
But the disease allowed me to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t want anything else in life,” she says, before letting her wear a breathing mask.
She is still waiting in the coming days for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy.
In the Viktor-Gadboy shelter, a group of volunteers provide body care and nutrition assistance.
This is palliative care, which remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, for every 11,700 inhabitants, there is one place in palliative care facilities.
This is very little, given that sooner or later we will all die.
Here life goes on in the best conditions possible, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors of the shelter.
Whether it is physical, emotional or emotional comfort.
To the dying we will agree to provide mouthwashes of brandy or pepsi, regardless of what he asks.
We no longer force diabetics to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought a beer to Mr. H., who died last night.
In the morning, his son drank this beer in the legs of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as well as patients,” says Natalie Savar, director of patient care.
In the shelter of Victor-Gadboi, not a single day is like the previous.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, lying on his pillows during a toast in his honor, a 36-year-old young man tragically dies, surrounded by parents, his wife and two young children and has tried everything to survive.
“In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadboi shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbow Hospice and the Palliative Care Society at the Greater Montreal Home, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is this big gap in Quebec’s health care system that has led many palliative care professionals to fear the adoption of a law that legalizes euthanasia and assisting suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by the Palliative Care Lights, Dr. Balfour Mountain and Dr. Bernard Lapuant, has been circulating and testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not effective enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the ambulance, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I'm afraid patients just want to die because they don't get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists try to save patients to the last day, despite pessimistic predictions.
The hopes for survival of Ellen Richard were already minimal when she stopped her exhausting chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was stopping the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered.
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for failing to comply with their request after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Society of Palliative Care at the Greater Montreal Home, said patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we are unaware of these sufferings.
More and more often, patients who do not manage to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients who suffer from pain always say the same phrase: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to have euthanasia,” it means “I want to have it easier.”
