Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
Bitcoin’s exchange rate, peaking at $30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, dropped five months later to $2, before returning to about $10 today (courses are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world’s exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
It describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competiting with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as “credits” used to promote a video game, which are earned during the game or which can be purchased (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are both bookkeepers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses, similar to an e-mail.
Only for each new payment the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information pertaining to this transaction is signed electronically, using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Due to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It passes through the solution of the mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, receives the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the hash phase of a file, that is, the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers “take” a new transaction and add a number to it before “hashing” them all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction is thus inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user would very quickly (in less than ten minutes) wish to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network – and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundred million, which leaves a reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
“The defect used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noaza, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes real-money payments using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
“Giant sales” were announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmkvist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noaza, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operational network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, making it cheaper.
The owner has better control over his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, Pierre Noaza clarifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Before Bitcoin is approved, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
In its report, the ECB envisages, by the way, to review the various risks that are considered increased today, if this system is successful.
We have left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Capisa and Surobi).
NATO and the U.S. should follow suit at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain control of its territory, and for the Afghans to choose their future, not relying only on us.
We were mainly affected by Afghan peasants, whom we considered terrorists.
And we ourselves, with 88 soldiers killed, wounded and mutilated.
The Taliban consists of foreign extremists, former commanders hiding in Pakistan, but also often of peasants who reject the presence of a foreign army, as it was in the USSR.
They want to protect their traditions, old and archaic, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
They are tolerated, they are sometimes helped by local rebels, but they will no longer be there as soon as the West becomes more delicate.
The withdrawal of French troops from the Nijraab base, which I observed from the heights of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French loans, was in order.
Convoys of trucks and armored vehicles accompanied by helicopters reached Kabul without being attacked.
Since the end of 2014, there will be no Taliban invasion of Kabul.
Circumstances have changed since their insurmountable advance from 1994 to 1996.
At that time Kabul was empty, the country was in fire and blood because of the struggles between different groups.
Their taking control of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women paid for the peasantry in which they were surpassed by al-Qaida, but their situation has not improved these days.
The former Mujahideen, the Afghan Government and the current Taliban are united in their desire to keep women subordinate.
The main characters of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into merchants seizing state land to resell it under construction to repatriates returning from Iran and Pakistan, using huge U.S. subcontracting contracts.
They are discredited; most of them, by the way, have not even fought themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, want a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have succeeded with American generosity: the outflow of capital is significant.
Young people are tired of war and its ideology.
They lived in the modern world during the exile in Iran or Pakistan, they appreciated its advantages.
About 65% of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one-fifth of the total population.
The public schools in the cities are filled with both boys and girls.
It is necessary to secure the jobs of these young people, who will not want to return either to the obscenity of the old parties or to the corruption of some leaders.
Everyone, including armed militants, loves mobile phones, television and Turkish soap operas that represent the modern world and that look everywhere.
There is an army at the moment.
Will the authorities that will command it be considered legitimate?
The old commanders, who led the anti-Soviet struggle, are already taking measures to restore provincial wives who would not obey the central authority.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local differences, should be decentralized to some extent, like Western countries, but the United States wanted to turn it into a centralized state with strong presidential power, eliminating the post of prime minister that existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign control, especially before the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country, starting in the 1950s and even earlier, is dependent on foreign aid.
The industry has not been put on its feet, no dam is functioning, no irrigation system has been repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except vegetables and fruits.
Priority is given to a private initiative.
In a country destroyed by thirty years of war, state control of infrastructure would be necessary.
There have been rumours that Afghanistan has enormous mineral wealth.
This only reinforced the feeling that Western countries were there only to capture them.
Without energy to recycle iron ore or copper on the spot, without means of transportation to export them through the mountains, there is no extraction of minerals.
The Chinese have almost left the Messi Aynak copper field, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to dig up a huge Buddhist complex and remain the province’s largest employers.
It is also necessary that one day Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports depend to a large extent, should restore normal relations.
The withdrawal of French combat units was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the preservation of traditional assistance: lyceum for girls, for boys, French language faculty at the university, French Institute, military, legal, medical and agricultural cooperation, support of the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, in an effort to "conquer hearts and minds" and to fulfill the impossible task of combining aid with offensive operations, the service of "military-civil activities" under the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012, together with a small French public organization, has contributed to the upswing of numerous public activities.
These works, with the intensive involvement of the local workforce, were able to help contain the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, forest restoration, fruit trees, soil protection and increasing the area of arable land.
What will we leave in memory of ourselves, spending two billion euros on military spending?
A much more modest budget would help improve the living conditions of the local population, which are very harsh in these valleys, often located at an altitude of more than 2,000 meters above sea level.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural works from local communities in the province of Capisa.
To get rid of the uprisings led by foreign groups, which the farmers want, as they told me, we need to provide them with a little non-military support that would be well controlled and treated directly.
Difficult Births of the Constitution of Egypt
This is a new risky move by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt is divided more than ever, on the issue of a constitutional declaration, which temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, he decided to play wa-bank.
Surprised, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
It has been almost two years since Egypt relied on the preliminary text, which had been amended several times, which weakened institutional stability and led to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only strengthened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his “autocratic delusion”, continuing to “violate this word” and “neglect the right”.
In the camp of his followers are confident that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis, accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce the intention to explain the text to the Egyptians, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent is raging across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Times.
The call for an accelerated vote resembles an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I retain my extraordinary powers”, which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday for the text.
Most liberals did not respond to the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they knocked on the door, feeling unable to express their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, spare members, were rushed to be added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day had arisen around... the time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was incorrectly tuned.
The text, which was still voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Object of general attention, article 2 ultimately remained the same as the 1971 article of the Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the primary source of law."
Salafist parties, for which the implementation of Islamic law is one of the basic requirements, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would allow for their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrite,” the liberals respond, who see this as a mere pyre.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular with regard to the verification of Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomiere, this is alarming, because "people called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy".
We can observe the birth of theocracy.”
Many liberals, moreover, are excited by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment there is no specific religious interference.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not wizards, but people with university education, some were trained in the French system," says Alexis Blois, who is preparing a dissertation on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that "around Article 220 there may be ambiguity, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, cf. ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to how competent civil judges are to make decisions on this."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is subject to criticism because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they have been significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another issue is the authority of the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the consideration of the defense budget will not take place in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Neither will the trial of civilians in military courts be prohibited, despite the requests of human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider to be detrimental to freedom.
Responsibility for blasphemy has been maintained, and insults are now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles talk about protecting women anymore, says Heba Moraef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, the demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will go out on the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy places, Pup of the Earth and the sea from the brine
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and the primacy of nature.
The AIF has outlined five of the most important reasons to visit Israel.
Let us worship the holy places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that everyone who enters this “dome” receives God’s grace.
And Galilee is the place of the miracles of Jesus: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here Jesus appeared before his disciples and after his resurrection.
Most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers here pass the Way of Sorrow or the Cross Path of Jesus (in Latin - Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antony - Pretoria - where there was a court, and through the streets of the Old City leads to the Temple of the Sepulchre of the Lord on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the Crucifixion, the Stone of Anointing and the place of the burial of Jesus.
Here is the symbolic Christian Pup of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem will be erected at the place where, according to Christian legend, a tree was grown, from which they made a cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the most holy place for the Jews - the Wall of Lamentation, left of the temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different denominations leave here notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Make a trip in a vertical manner
The ruins of the fortress of Massada remained from the secret refuge from enemies that Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on steep cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And only those who are passionate about mountaineering can reach them.
The rest are taken to this historic summit by a cable car lift.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, which in the winter months - a huge influx of tourists.
There is a shuttle bus at the foot of the mountain.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient tradition, pagan gods supposedly lived on top of the mountain.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are about 300 museums in the country.
You don’t get to visit everyone in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It contains the oldest Qumran manuscripts, or scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
It is also worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exhibition are widely represented paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Acco, you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which represents several halls of ancient Turkish baths with paintings of visitors and bankers of the time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dalí and Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are not accepted.
The fifth - the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells about one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section - the children's memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk into it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are waving.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned here.
Healing
The three main resort areas of Israel are located on the coasts of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
It is interesting that in the Red Sea bathe even in the winter months, because the water temperature there does not fall below 21 degrees of heat, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and bathes there all year round.
By the way, this is the most extraordinary sea in the world is at the lowest point on the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a salt, which easily keeps floating even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes around it are unrealistically beautiful.
Go here to undergo a course of treatment with the use of salt water - rapeseed, and healing dirt, and to treat health with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes mellitus, to bring in order the shaken.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are stored by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the city of Jaffa on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
Through it passed the famous Sea Route, connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom here they lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to wander through the narrow streets named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say if you hit the walls on the street of "your" sign, Fortune will be favored.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries in a photo shoot.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can roam the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourist on the note
When traveling to Israel, do not worry about your imperfect English: in the country about 30% of the population knows the Russian language.
The money for the trip is better to take not in euros, but in dollars, which are easy to exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar - 3.8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly buses, but in Jerusalem there is a high-speed tram, and in Haifa - the only subway line in the country, consisting of six stations and connecting the Lower City with the Upper.
In fact, it's an underground funicular.
Travel in all types of urban transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive with transfers within 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop working.
And on Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, there is only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, peel-free fish and dishes that combine milk with meat.
There is a wide selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts cooked on coconut milk, traditional Jewish paste humus, a variety of sauces, balls of hammered nut - falalel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israel.
But there are a lot of fed cats that walk on their own.
In the evening, they can be seen sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Murleys love crowded places and do not refuse meals.
Car rental, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $15 per day.
And renting a bicycle will cost 15 shekels. per day.
Tickets to museums cost on average 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the travel and rest came from citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Great and powerful" to Moscow will lead: migrants will save money on language
While deputies and human rights defenders argue that the law on compulsory language testing will, fraudsters have already appeared in the country, trading "lip" certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only purpose is to earn money to support the families that remain in the homeland.
As of December 1, a law has entered into force, according to which every migrant worker will be obliged to pass an exam for knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the field of services, housing and utilities, households and retail.
However, over time, the FMS promises, tests will become mandatory for all visitors.
At the same time, it will be necessary to surrender not only the language, but also the Russian history and the basics of the legislation.
Language proficiency will have to be confirmed both for obtaining and for extending the work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the state language.
They are not subject to the law and people who managed to obtain certificates and diplomas of education before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Use, condemnation and protection of rights
The network of examination points will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of the Friendship of Nations, the MSU, the SPbSU and other Russian universities.
Migrants will be able to pass tests in all cities; already more than 160 such centers have opened in Russia.
The initiative on introducing testing was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the FMS.
But human rights defenders, before the law came into force, many times managed to ask the press the question: what does this actually mean?
What will change the compulsory knowledge of the language for both Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First of all, according to the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "labour slavery".
Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains the head of the Russian FMS mission in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelev.
The protection of their rights must begin before they leave.
Only the system of organized recruitment will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise in migrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language, who do not have a medical certificate.
Without understanding the language, the future migrant is doomed to face unfaithful people who, under the guise of help, will throw him a “guide” into a scary narrow barrack, where he and dozens of others will spend months without food and documents, squeezing 12-14 hours a day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland they are promised one thing, and on arrival they are deceived, they take passports, they do not pay the promised salary," - confirms the head of the main department of labor migration of the Ministry of Labor of Tajikistan Tolib Sharipov.
Don't fight me, man!
However, while many citizens of Central Asian republics who are going to earn money in Russia admit that they not only do not know the language of the country in which they aspire, but also write hard on their own.
Of course, it is not so much their fault as their trouble: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford even an intelligent primary education.
After all, their families have nothing even to feed the children, not to mention, to dress them decently, to shoes and to equip them for school.
Growing up to adolescence, such guys go to earnings at the first opportunity.
It’s hard if they don’t know the language, they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inadequate."
However, with regard to the language law, human rights defenders note one important point.
Testing will be conducted only for those migrants who have legal status.
If there is no status, there will be no examination or subsequent official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers still live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or Alien Entrance Banned"
Many of the visitors claim that getting official status in our country is not so easy.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and all the same language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But the fake registration can be done quickly and for only half a thousand.
Russian police officers know that we have mostly fake documents, no registration, hence cases of extortion.
"One hundred, two for cigarettes, tea", - shared with journalists citizen of Tajikistan Umad Huschadamov.
"Fly, don't rush, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the law on language, it was found that not only migrant registration documents are fake.
Several "lip" certificates of passing language tests have already been confiscated by FMS staff.
Fake papers are printed on a regular color printer.
Of course, they got to the new owners not in vain: each of the migrants, who hoped to make it easier for themselves to pass the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is two times more expensive than the official testing procedure: it will cost a migrant worker three thousand.
The main task in the near future is to protect the system from corruption, so that the "steps" can not be simply bought, both the authorities and human rights defenders agree.
So far, the authorities can promise guest workers who have not been able to successfully pass the test from the first time, time to study the basic language course.
In addition, visitors who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs does not take into circulation the illegal arms market
The proportion of crimes using legal weapons is extremely low.
The Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs proposes to tighten the law against the owners of civilian weapons.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: to press gunfire at weddings when there were no victims, and the massacre organized by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, as a result of which seven people were killed.
Police want to ban the wearing of trauma in public places and raise the age at which you can get a gun license - from 18 years to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Countering Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, and promised that amendments to the arms law will be introduced in the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities are trying to combat the problem by “turning nuts.”
An open letter appeared on the network, the authors of which - representatives of various public small-scale organizations - demand to abandon the "senseless tightening".
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, said the Russian service of the BBC forensic lawyer Vasily Lesnikov.
According to the Ministry of Internal Affairs, in the six months of 2012, 142 crimes were committed with the use of firearms, registered in the bodies of internal affairs, while in the same period alone, 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are sure that the tightening of the legislation in the field of civil weapons does not allow the criminal to go to the "black" market.
Now, according to them, in Moscow you can find any weapon at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Internal Affairs claims to be controlling the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The "black" arms market is replenished through several channels.
The main channels are five, says retired Colonel Viktor Baranets, who worked for ten years in the structure of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
