Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and took an active part in a number of ESA projects in the following years.
But Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in spaceflights, but this was not always met with understanding.
I would like to recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Space".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltri and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his "Introduction to Space".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned propagandist of space science, and his contribution was appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the back of the Moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland was built a railway train, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether the rocket had to be used for acceleration or to brake the truck.
Information about this dressage is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The study was carried out by the Arms Engineering Section in cooperation with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzhitsky.
From the preserved materials, it can be seen that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, work was interrupted.
In 1937, in the specialized press, the idea of a photoelectric rocket-fighter, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, appeared, and the following year, the work "Air rocket-torpedo and aviation rocket-bomb" by the author Levya-Kzhivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war itself, all the projects of military use of missile equipment were handled by the Temporary Scientific and Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation the work was completed due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work, devoted to space science, appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronauticze).
For the first time about the society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine "Problems", which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovic proposed to organize a society that will be engaged in space.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn POA became a valid member.
The following year, Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902-1959) became the first president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Raketa Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of overcoming a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, tests of a two-stage RM-2 rocket were conducted at the Bled Desert.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight - 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 l, Meteor-1V - 0.34 l, and Meteor-1S - 0.62 l.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
Thereafter, versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Studies) in 1960 and the establishment of the National Committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmologist after Vladimir Remec.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution to the problem.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The decision sparked a lively debate in society.
It will undoubtedly be interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and free, unrestricted movement of private capital along with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of a significant difference in the value of labour-power (wages), a price tension arises.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the state in which the producer, by means of the delivery of a cheap commodity, tries to resist economic competition by "defeating" the value of the competitor in order to take over the greater part of the market and thereby increase his own income.
On a massive scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either transferring production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or disappearing. As a result, unemployment increases in those countries where the cost of labor, compared to others, is high.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility, including for the unemployment it produces, the inevitable expenditures of the state on social needs are increasing.
In general, the situation increases the reluctance of employers to pay taxes and thus compensate for the social economic and social damage they inflict in pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that there is no need to provide specific statistics.
The unceremonious methods of private capital create at the level of individual states’ economies a situation where governments of countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give their own population to private capital at will, despite social decline.
This is reflected primarily in the changes to the current legislation.
The aim is to economically force its people to submit to the dictates of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This acts as a system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool to reduce the rights of workers in the field of labour law.
As a result, the poverty rate increases and, at the same time, the gap between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, for several years, there has been a public distribution of food to the poor, who are unable to feed themselves with their own labor.
The number of these people is approaching a million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, there are constantly cases where the employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra for them to get a living minimum.
