If capital comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, as a Chinese, Hindu, Brazilian, Turk, Moroccan, Egyptian, African still works for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media up to the nausea claim that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists that the state should not intervene in the economy through its governing actions.
Next, the question should be answered, is private capital, now practically managing politics and thus the entire state, not acting for its own selfish purposes?
The unambiguous answer is yes.
The evidence is the existence of virtually omnipotent and omnipresent lobbying in all states.
As a result, we have a hopeless situation, manifested in corruption, in ensuring mutual benefits, in legislation, where almost everything deserves punishment, but is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that, due to a lack of funds, state ministries commission the development of bills to private law firms that are closely associated with the industry.
The bills are then approved by the Bundestag.
All power comes not from the people, as the constitution of the Western type states, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal-oriented democracy is now rapidly finding itself in a situation as described by Appian in the "Crisis of the Roman Empire in the days of Caesar and Pompey": "The state has long been disintegrating and the agencies are engaged in violence.
Bribery, unlawful receiving of mercy by means of stones and swords.
The corruption and bribery flourished without any prohibitions, and the people went to the elections with a pre-sold vote"...decent people at all did not run for the position of ruler, at the end of the day the state was left without a consul for eight months. .. ..
As in antiquity, in modern society, their own reckless interests prevail without taking into account the public interest.
Private capital is no longer intended to be used for public purposes.
The present result is no different from the past: an unprecedented decline of the elite without any attempt to carry out reforms of a deeper nature.
So the cause of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes we must seek in the reckless liberalization of economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
To date, the absence of these regimes and the existence of a liberal democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite is completely ignoring the consequences for the hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing, along with the crimes against humanity as we know it from old and new history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a decision, or at least not forever.
Under the pressure of competition at both international and national and European levels, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore of a systemic nature.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the participation of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in the management of the state and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society in favor of the state.
