"Operation Argo: When There's Nowhere Worse, Call Hollywood"
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist protesting students seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution in the United States, who were the patrons of his regime for decades.
The U.S. administration was not expecting a positive outcome - it could not afford to throw the chess overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the confidence of the allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were finally released 444 days later, after negotiations brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate evoked at home a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments.
The defeat in Iran greatly contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, "Operation Argo" describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult journeys, they finished their journey at the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, with the help of an extravagant cover-up legend, according to which they traveled on Canadian passports as members of a film crew, looking for a place in the country to shoot a science fiction epic.
A combination of genres
The plan, invented by evacuation expert Tony Mendes, demanded Hollywood cooperation.
To make the legend credible, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, held press conferences, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, a film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-kinoopus", the story of a successful case, a hoax - an example can be a series of movies about friends of Oushen.
The film constantly changes the mood - on the one hand, documentary scenes from Tehran (the headlines show iconic historical photographs of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, light Hollywood excerpts interspersed with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, on the staircases of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck had a great career reboot.
From a ridiculous actor became a respected director, and his play ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, baby, goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film not to be shot in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feel of the atmosphere of the place refers to the qualities that elevated the director’s earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it at Argo, where Tehran is playing Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets when real events are reconstructed – the opening scenes of the embassy’s fall impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when history suddenly changes.
A similar effect Affleck and his colleagues achieve in the scenes of fiction (a fake headquarters on a Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the story does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes he thinks of something - there it all comes out not so elegantly (a scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at Tehran airport, and chasing on the runway look pretty lame).
The drawback of Argo is the distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of drama, it’s a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the production and retro-style, recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to catch up.
However, this is enough to remind us of one, still in a certain sense, living story, as well as to testify how exaggerated are the notions of omnipotent and omniscient intelligence.
