The architects of MVRDV prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speykenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“This building seems fun to me, it looks futuristic, we can finally see something interesting again,” says Lizette Verhaig, who walks along the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, says, “No, this building is really beautiful.”
But I ask myself, why do we have another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad and e-books.
No one wants to go to such old-fashioned libraries anymore, right?
Speykenisse, a small sleeper town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted concrete miniatures.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the city’s fathers realized that they had only one chance to beat the statistics: to build a library here!
Vini Maas of Rotterdam’s architectural bureau MVRDV, a master of bold column diagrams and author of clever, sometimes even cynical, constructions, addressed the task with his usual unhingedness and appeared at a 2003 competition audition with five books under his arm and ear.
And while the jury members looked back and squeezed their shoulders, the daring Maas made a pyramid of his original gift of size and concluded his speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here's my suggestion: "The Book Mountain" in Speykenis, the so-called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, grew.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential houses and townhouses totaling 50 apartments.
In early November, "Book Mountain" was awarded the second prize of the competition "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch National Wooden Structures Competition.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which before it could offer nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly unsightly town hall, whose white facades suggest a dairy factory, has become richer in one modern work of architecture.
But most importantly - in Speykenis appeared the first in the history of this city a public building of cultural purpose.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: the Eldorado book under the hood for cheese.
There is only one elevator passing in the center of the mountain range, because true lovers of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
The glazed room on all sides is bright and easily visible, the floors made of burnt brick and elegant street lamps unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly restored.
The eye involuntarily looks for benches, dogs and football players boys and girls.
Everywhere, books, books, books.
“Usually book shelves stand along the facades, and in the middle is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Vini Maas.
We put the classic configuration of the space from the feet to the head and pulled out the reading area from the inside out.
The interior space of the book mountain is skillfully used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical premises.
Particularly pleased are the black bookshelves, which serve as a decoration of the walls, railings and stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even tempted architects and engineers are lost in guesses, what is this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with secondary materials,” explains Jop Trauborst, the project manager representing the Speykenisse community, in line with the requirements of the standard.
And at one agribusiness in Friesland, we found a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fiber material of millimeter thickness has been used as a lining under the roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textile serves one or two seasons, after which it can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplastik (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a little like a new car and a little sneakers.
105 steps lead to the top.
Anyone who crosses the nearly 500-metre-long path will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquets and wooden figs in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first and foremost about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
The Cost of a New Soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days, the sun only enters for a short time.
Wide farms made of glued wood, located perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lizette Verhaig has been here as well.
Cynthia Bogard, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, called Buchenberg “the soul of the Speykenisse that has long been lacking.”
The reason: a few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from his own congregation.
These books were supposed to occupy empty seats on the shelves of a library not yet fully equipped - at the time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are upstairs.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Vinnie Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation now every resident is in some way connected to this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal problem, which in professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Speykenisse wrote his literary history.
They are very young and unskilled.
This is just the starting point for building an identity.
Sabo: "Germans should play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinians’ application for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
What's that?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely moving from a policy that, so to speak, was run by the United States, to actually German foreign policy.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent single policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are only sensing their role so far, but they are on their way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
Such foreign policy as is carried out by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position in their national interests, independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf states.
It must therefore be cautious not to offend the public and elites in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays a role.
But I wouldn’t attach too much importance to this, it’s not a completely one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Did Germany harm its relations with the United States by abstaining from important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think that it was as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are differing views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The U.S., on the other hand, has vetoed it.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of U.S. domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as significant as it always seems.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a single, non-contradictory European policy, but now it is not.
Therefore, they cannot act within a broader approach and are forced to act instead based solely on their own vision of the situation.
That’s what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future, Germany will take on a leading role in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been skeptical.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take on the leading role?
Or is it still hard to give Germany a leading role?
Germany is not accustomed to this yet, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis – every time Germany takes on an important role, there are various anti-German sentiments.
The Germans can’t just deal with it.
Actually, this is an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to take into account a variety of neighbors and opinions, which is not easy.
So, the U.S. influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will have to play a bigger role.
Even if you do not like it, unpleasant or increases the dislike for you - such is life!
Stephen Sabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America jointly explore the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
