These measures are clear blows to the democratic rules of the game and will lead the Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening the civilian state, the president de facto cancelled it,” Saeda said.
Without civil society, democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels that everyone has left him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of directions on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There may be a repayment for that.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: "You are creating a monster that you cannot control."
Norwegian codfish: the worst-smelling fish in the world?
Norway’s five million population has one of the highest living standards not only in Europe but also around the world.
Perhaps the secret of the success of this country is somehow connected with the local addiction to one extremely malicious fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sportswear.
Leave them there for a week.
You will get a sparkling smell of rakfisk - one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I am in a small town called Fagernes, three hours’ drive from Oslo.
Around the snow-capped picturesque views. It is very beautiful, but the inextinguishable characteristic odor spreads in the air.
Raccoon is a trout sprinkled with salt and wandered in the water for up to a year, depending on what kind of sting you need to achieve.
As twilight thickens and cools, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes, dedicated to this very, so to speak, exciting dish.
"It is eaten raw and drunk with a slice of aquavit, local mint vodka," explains Harvard Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and co-chairman of the "Raffisk general", who leads the festival.
Everywhere around us, people eat fish cut into small cubes and drink it with large amounts of alcohol.
“Somebody likes aquavit more than raccoon,” says Harvard.
This drink is capable of breaking the smell.
I'll try a couple of pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - it is little different from the portion of land that you took with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, a time of poverty, when, even before the emergence of refrigerators, fish were soaked in hermetically sealed barrels of salt water in the fall.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish was already well and thoroughly digested, it was extracted and, by silencing the perception with alcohol, consumed in food.
In memory of the past generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States.
Nowadays, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are attracted here by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a long-time rival, and not so long ago and a much more affluent neighbor) come here massively to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat sinister, element of Norway’s past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you 9 pounds ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world’s news, and most of the country’s residents seem to agree.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called “the July 22 attack.”
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of Norway’s current prosperity is the growth (since the early 1970s) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“However, oil isn’t the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress, who wears trays with long-lasting raffia, a woman with long blond hair and strikingly blue eyes, the embodiment of Nordic well-being.
We are such a people, as you call it, wise.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks English very well.
We don't like to show up, we don't brag.
Norway is very careful with its oil – most of the revenue of the oil and gas industry is invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was messing around with money they didn’t have, Norway sparingly calculated all the costs.
“While you can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there's a raccoon," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in the snow in a queue for some food - I'll have enough raffia.
Here's a hamburger with salmon meat - it's definitely exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
In my hotel there is a special dinner dedicated to raffisk, during which visitors vote to determine the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a live TV show, which shows the lead in a butterfly tie, surrounded by plates with raffia.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jürgen, what grade did you give for the best fish there in the mountains?"
"Yes, Harvard, here's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone's falling from a chair, maybe over the aquavit.
Or maybe just breathing in the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto will face a difficult start to his career.
As Mexico’s newly elected president Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
Traffic in Mexico City is in a particularly bad state.
This city is overloaded with transport and at the best of times, and since Monday, steel fences have been erected, intersecting several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was done not to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will wear the presidential bandage and take the reins of the country.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderón, who is now in power, but the country has sunk in a war on drugs that has already claimed about 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Peña Nieto told US President Barack Obama earlier this week in the White House’s oval office.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, alongside the US President, Mr. Peña Nieto’s political career developed as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the country’s capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Straight-line man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
The inhabitants put in his credit the revival of tourism, the development of the resort sphere and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are markedly different from the roads with protrusions and pits that used to be in this place.
The signs with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We have hopes for real and serious change with him,” said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a state congressman from the Peña Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We expect real and decisive changes, which are so urgently needed by our country, especially in the area of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was displaced in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence at the presidential palace in Los Pinos, the party places great hopes on Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he denies the accusations of incontinence put forward by the opposition to the new president.
He is very straightforward and very committed to embodying his vision of the future of the country.
He is an excellent politician and, above all, a person who is able to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nesaualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nessa, is the most striking contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden beneath the intersections of highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality also bear the harsh nature of this metropolis.
Troops were recruited earlier this year to appease drug trafficking gangs in those areas, and violence against women is particularly acute here.
Dozens of bodies of murdered women have been found in the desert near an extensive landfill in the last two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in the state of Mexico during the government of Mr. Peña Nieto, far exceeding that in the infamous city of Ciudad Juárez, whose name has become nicknamed when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to opponents of Mr. Peña Nieto, at best, it can be said that during his tenure as Governor, he was unable to cope with the problem of killing women.
In the worst case scenario, his administration is accused of completely ignoring this problem.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most of the houses in this outdated area, Irina Buendía has a hard time holding back her tears by showing me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her cohabitant killed her.
"When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed away before that," Buendía recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and her body was already stranded.
Mariana’s mother recounts this story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to the crucifix, on which only one word is drawn: justice.
This, they said, was denied to the family.
“State officials treated me like an old gossip, dissatisfied with the disturbance.
They want people to just believe everything they say and keep quiet.
But that’s not right, that’s not possible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around,” she says.
Having worn the presidential bandage on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
In the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violence-related crimes, and the new president has pledged to make a solution to this problem a priority during his reign.
“I hope that he will be exactly the same president as he was the governor,” said Olvera, a congressman from the Valle de Bravo PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
Bradley Manning has not complained of mistreatment, the prosecution said.
Prosecutors are trying to disprove Bradley Manning’s claims of poor detention conditions.
The hearing focused on Manning's stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning’s conditions of detention were cruel.
The U.S. military has been accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that plaintiff Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified materials in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had to transfer while in military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, Military Prosecutor Major Ashden Fein said that records of Manning's weekly visits by the prison administration for nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia.
A cross-examination of Manning ' s application to terminate the case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves a sufficient punishment was conducted the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks has not confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
During the hearing on Friday, Prosecutor Fein and Manning reviewed reports that were completed after Manning’s visits by administration officials during his time in Quantico Prison, where he was in a strict detention regime from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked on Friday about the reports, Manning admitted that he assessed the prison administration's treatment of him as "excellent" and the general terms of detention as "very professionally organized".
The reports under review do not contain any complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being explicitly asked about the terms of his detention, says Fein.
Manning replied that he had expressed his oral concern about the problems and that the representatives of his administration who had visited had discussed the problems with him and had stated that they would deal with them, but had not recorded it in writing.
“They recorded ‘problems are absent’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t raise the issue in the conversation,” Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Linde, also asked Manning why he hadn’t complained about being mistreated in January 2011 during a committee meeting that considered the suicide intentions he had expressed in writing a few months before.
Manning responded that during the meeting he wanted to have the “prevention of injury” regime removed from him and to mitigate the conditions of detention.
Military officials explained that a limited regime of detention - to a level lower than the regime of surveillance to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them canceling the injury prevention regime ... so that my life level improves, from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday of his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait, and that one day he had lost consciousness because of the intense heat.
He explained that psychologically it is very difficult when you are not told how your destiny is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison,” Manning said on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in this cage."
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day — in complete solitude.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, slippers, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying down during the day was prohibited by the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, the light in his eyes was constantly penetrating the outside of the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned in bed at night, he said, he was awakened and forced to turn his back.
Manning's lawyer filed an official objection to Manning's mistreatment in January 2011.
Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
In addition, a judge on Friday asked Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners in the morning.
Manning said he was unable to cover the blanket during the inspection.
Responding to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's orders that he should throw a blanket that he could cover, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to throw it.
Manning said on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked last night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told the officer that he could use a rubber pantyhose or slippers to injure himself, but did not.
That night, Manning testified, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from the cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to endure during his imprisonment and significantly shorten the term of imprisonment if Manning is found guilty by the military court, which should begin his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and challenge other charges as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims Manning was detained in Quantico under rules governing the contents of detainees with the strictest regime.
The charges brought against Manning include co-opting the enemy, illegally facilitating the disclosure of data on the Internet, transferring information related to national defense, and hijacking of state property or documents.
If convicted of all charges, he may face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind people of the country’s difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American descent are splitting between the two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked through the arrival corridor, approached the border control zone and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two rows: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and have been called a Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later I stopped at the complex design of "American of Mexican descent".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
That’s why I got my American passport and became a queue for the Extranjeros.
I recalled this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Peña Nieto has eagerly spoken about the rise of the Mexican economy, which will allow Mexicans now, with the same success, to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto has promised to continue the war on drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals have been made.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is a heavy, old-fashioned issue.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and, under the rifles, forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only worth to any U.S. official to silence at least a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elite of Mexican society immediately there are complaints that the Americans are invading the sovereignty of neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with belligerence.
At the same time, Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is the most difficult.
Want to talk about insults?
Enough of them.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country for themselves, and those for whom there is no such opportunity.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for just one reason: at some point in their family history, no one – father or grandfather – was able to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go to Mexico.
Most often, they were Mexicans of a certain type - slumped, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got a good job, but let's not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider our own.
The United States of America.
In addition, we know that most representatives of the Mexican elite and ruling class do not like us.
We respond to them the same way.
They see in us a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as unreal Mexicans.
We do not speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We wouldn’t be behind the silk curtain now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual bonds.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and this reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican descent - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Americans understand the pro-Mexican identities.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican descent do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of two worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
We are Americans in Mexico.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship was already not sufficiently confusing, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to rebuild relations with the diaspora.
They want Americans of Mexican descent to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent their interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit, and we could persuade political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not gonna work.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the spread of corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not find this country so beautiful.
Excuse me, but take care of it yourself, Amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will also have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican descent are still offended by how they dealt with their relatives recently in Mexico.
Yeah, yeah.
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
The Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is there a long-term peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
The usual, meaningless controversy over who started first; many buildings have been turned into ruins; over 140 Palestinians, most of whom were civilians, and six Israelis, have been killed; for the first time in the conflict, the rockets fired from the territory of the Gaza Strip have been fired.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians have been hopelessly caught up in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the "Arab Spring" have engulfed many established realities in a rebellious storm, and the Palestinians with the Israelis have not managed to stay away from the whirlwind that has shaken the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give reason for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes that took place this week have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in Gaza in 2007, will say they have forced Israel to retreat despite the losses it has suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders have been wiped out and 1.7 million people blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has failed to wipe out Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity on the West Bank of the Jordan River, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time works for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and rich friends.
The emerging regional leader Turkey, once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing Gulf states.
Hamas supporters proclaim the creation of an Islamic crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, which is ruled by the paramilitary group Hezbollah, to Syria, in which more and more pro-Islam rebels are about to overthrow the power of Bashar Assad.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where under President Mohammed Mursi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to Hamas’ support.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the "hard" line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli anti-missile system Iron Dome justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas missiles launched.
The citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully, at least for some time.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained true to its unchanged stance; many European countries have also blamed the start of the last round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004 about 30 Israelis have been killed by missiles fired from the territory of the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide terrorists, partly due to the wall that enters the territory of the West Bank.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - as part of the preparations for the January 22 elections - has joined with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of giving the Palestinians their own state?
If we give them all the power in the West Bank, won’t they start launching rockets from there toward Israel, as do their counterparts in the Gaza Strip?
It is better to hold them behind the wall and firmly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Supporters of the "hard" line may win; however, their calculations may be refuted by the Arab Spring.
Although the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defensive part of Israel’s budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Unleashing a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egypt’s President Mursi, who worked with Barack Obama on the ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to a lesser extent, must take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes take place in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a slow-acting bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, similar to the bus blasted in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement are being paid by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need an external impetus.
There remains the only solution that has been relentlessly called for by sane representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and Israel’s surrender of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the sides of the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long since decided to block arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, have a more advantageous position than ever to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming vote at the UN, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
Its role in putting Israel at the negotiating table should also be played by President Obama.
During his first term, he never presented his own plan for a peaceful settlement.
After returning to the White House, he continues to show his reluctance to join in solving the problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on unified packaging for cigarettes has entered into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and images of disease-affected parts of the body are contrasted on depressing green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in the world practice Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products has entered into force, replacing the logos and color scheme of different brands with the same box of depressed-olive color with horrific pictures of their sickness of smoking parts of the body and images.
In addition to the various pictures and inscriptions warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packets introduced in mandatory order from this Saturday - the names of the stamps, which are printed with the same small font.
These are the world’s toughest conditions for packaging tobacco products.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the purpose of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving this harmful habit of fashion status.
Research shows that people who have not started smoking before the age of 26 in 99 out of 100 cases never become smokers.
“It’s obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey by designing packaging,” explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing research that shows that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a child’s fingerprint.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest smoking rate in the world, so these changes will not have a significant impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market on which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will lead to serious consequences other than those conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of small family-owned company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for cigarette butts and silicone cases hiding unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from zero) since two months ago, companies such as British American Tobacco, British Tobacco, and British Imperial Tobacco were brought to trial.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 products to wholesale companies and is waiting for a new batch.
This is a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, in the opinion of experts, the popularity of social networks among the segment of the population targeted by these measures.
Following the adoption in Australia of a number of laws that made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sporting events, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from posting ads online, but it cannot restrict foreign sites from doing so.
“If you trade in tobacco products and you only have this small loophole left, the idea of promoting your product online will seem extremely tempting to you,” explains Becky Freeman, a researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of reviews on brands written by supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is it really a matter of the hands of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he did not spare the effort and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
Representatives of the tobacco industry have even gone to such measures as sponsorship of Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims within the World Trade Organization, stating that trade has been subjected to unfair restrictions, despite the fact that the trade relations with all these countries.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tani Plibersek, the government has discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to impose the mandatory posting of photos warning of the dangers of smoking.
This rule has now been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstratively disobedient to innovation.
These pictures don't bother me.
I'm just not paying attention.
“You just grab a cigarette and hide the package in your pocket,” explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the package.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yu, the head of the King of the Pack tobacco store in downtown Sydney, claims that the same packaging has made it difficult to arrange goods on shelves.
"I used to have an hour to unload the new batch, and now four hours," he complains.
"The government should have taken and completely banned cigarettes, we would have said: what to do, okay, it's all over, we're closing the store," he says, raising his hands.
Missing the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane, which we were waiting for.
So I had enough time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna fool you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and books, magazines, iPhones, even duty-free shops will not help much.
However, in recent times, more and more scientists and specialists in child development are speaking in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations for us and for our children to miss is not so bad.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass by us.
Perhaps we need to strive for boredom?
Oh, yes.
And at the same time, it's not.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think, like many, that boredom was a relatively recent invention when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient history," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating from the first century.
The question remains as to how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research materials on this topic and asking a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came up with the following definition: boredom is when people “want but can’t do what would bring them satisfaction.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person does not do something he would like to do.
I don’t want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in the boredom experienced, he says, is “a disturbance of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is slowly stretching.”
As described, boredom can seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these conditions, missing people see the causes of problems in the surrounding world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel like we’re bored when in fact we’re just having a hard time focusing on something.
In his study “Unemployed Mind: Defining Boredom from Attention Point of View,” published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues cited a previous experiment in which participants listened to a voice recording reading the journal.
Some participants also heard loud sounds not related to the case of the television program included in the neighboring room, others heard the same sounds at low volume, so that they could hardly be disassembled, and the third group only listened to the recording of the voice without a foreign soundtrack.
Those participants who listened to low-volume TV noted that they were bored, more often than others - they were difficult to concentrate, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, distractions can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, “for example, looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom.”
It is believed that when people begin to rock on a chair or draw crabs on a sheet of paper, they do so out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions simply help not to relax physically.
"The study found that children who are not forbidden to wander and wander learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit quietly," Fenske said.
At times we all get bored: with a flight delay (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show different degrees of propensity to boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a special “boring propensity scale” to measure such individual characteristics.
To determine the assessment on such a scale, questions and statements are used, for example, "A lot of what I have to do is uniform and monotonous" or "I have too much interest, so there is not enough time for anything."
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys miss girls more often, says Steven Vodanovic, a professor of psychology at the University of Western Florida, especially with a variety of external stimuli.
In general, however, teenagers are often missed.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he interacted with nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
32% of teenagers said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data would be about boredom now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “teenage age has a peak of boredom” mainly because children and teenagers are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let’s return to my original question: is boredom useful?
Sometimes it doesn’t, because in extreme manifestations, research shows, it can push people to absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling, or substance abuse in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the link between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to studying this problem.
“So our brain tells us to do something else; that’s boredom,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, the brain itself does not always know what to do better.
If you get bored and you focus that energy on playing the guitar or cooking experiments, you’ll do better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child misses and you give him an iPad, he will stop missing, but he will not learn to fight boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and employment, says Professor Fenske.
“And such self-regulatory skills are used in a variety of situations,” he says.
Your child not only learns to do something on his own, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think boredom has to be praised.
However, it is not worth considering it as a bad thing either.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of actions and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
“We see this in such a way that we need to experience boredom more often, even though boredom is an extremely unpleasant, inexhaustible desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In today’s world, we are accustomed to constant excessive stimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when silence comes, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
It is unclear how the new law on the legalization of marijuana in the state of Colorado will apply.
Anthony Orosco, a nineteen-year-old football team player and a public college student in southeastern Colorado, is accused of committing a criminal offense that will soon be completely legal throughout the state: storing a small portion of his marijuana and pipes.
Mr. Orosco says that one day in September he and his friends were in Lamar and were driving in a car across the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in a car, Mr. Orosco was ordered to appear in court for drug possession and possession of a device for drug use - small offenses, each of which is fined $100 - and a date for the trial was set.
“We are treated like criminals,” Mr. Orosco said.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that continues for weeks after the state of Colorado voted to legalize marijuana use in small amounts for entertainment, the solution of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law, but on the place of consideration.
Accusations of minor marijuana-related offences have already been dropped in hundreds of cases here and in the state of Washington, which has taken a similar measure.
Police stations have already stopped charging people aged 21 and older with storing small doses, which will be considered legal as soon as the law enters into force in a few weeks.
However, in the more conservative Colorado counties, prosecutors have decided to consider existing marijuana cases and are still prosecuting for storing the drug.
At the same time, in some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous areas of the West, they are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from appearing in their locations.
“It’s all happening so fast that I don’t even know what to expect next,” said Daniel J. Outs, a police chief in the town of Aurora, east of Denver.
Representatives of the controlling authorities in the state of Washington are also intrigued to scratch their heads.
They will have to establish rules to determine the procedure for licensing the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done by 1 December 2013.
They say that Colorado, good or bad, is ahead of most other states in dealing with marijuana use, first for medical purposes, and now for entertainment.
“Colorado has a more orderly market, so they will serve as a good example,” explains Brian I. Smith, a representative of the Council for Regulating the Production and Sales of Alcohol Products in Washington State.
But now no one can do more, admits Mr. Smith, than to make some suggestions and hope that it will work.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we could focus on,” he says.
The Washington state bill, dubbed I-502, will come into force on December 6 and will put the state in a state of uncertainty for a whole year when state licensing systems are not yet in place and the right to own marijuana has already been legalized.
And there are still difficult technical aspects that need to be addressed during this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order on "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on its trade at a distance of 1,000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
“It will be particularly difficult to place licensed marijuana businesses in urban areas, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,” explains Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly established Marijuana Legalization Center research group.
On November 21, Aurora Police Chief Outs emailed his subordinates that the city's prosecutor's office would no longer hold people under the age of 21 to account for possession of a small amount of marijuana, and that the police were stopping the moment of "detecting" people in these violations.
Police chief Outs said police would monitor the city’s compliance with regulations governing the activities of people growing marijuana for medical purposes and would prosecute illegal traffickers and drug dealers.
Weld County District Attorney for Northern Colorado, Ken Buck, presents a more rigorous approach to the issue.
Following the vote on the bill, he stated that the prosecution would continue to hold the possession of marijuana accountable, mainly to encourage its users to undergo treatment.
At the moment, 119 people have been charged with storing two or less ounces of marijuana, although many of them are accused of other violations.
“It is the duty of our institution to prosecute for acts that are considered criminal at the time of their commission,” Buck said in a statement.
The reaction was ambiguous even in places such as the rural district of Mesa, where the voters rejected the proposal to legalize marijuana.
Grand Junction Police, the largest city in the county, no longer holds adults responsible for possessing a small amount of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Houtzinger backed the decision, but also decided not to dismiss the charges in already open cases related to marijuana storage.
“I believe it is our direct responsibility to enforce the law until it changes,” he said.
Despite the fact that 55% of Colorado residents who took part in the vote supported this decision, including the use of marijuana for entertainment in the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the conflicting reaction of residents in different parts of the state exposed the ambiguity of the attitude of the local authorities to the state experiment with marijuana.
“The district attorneys have a cultural barrier in this matter,” explains Sean MacAllister, a Denver lawyer representing the interests of those convicted of marijuana possession, and a local representative of the National Marijuana Law Reform Organization.
“They’ve been harassing people for so long that they can’t really accept that it’s not a crime anymore,” he says.
Colorado and Washington, the first states to treat marijuana in the same way as alcohol, are destined to become a nationwide experimental field to test the very idea of drug legalization.
Proponents of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time they are cautiously awaiting instructions from the federal authorities, who still plan to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Proponents of marijuana legalization hope that the Office of Justice will give way in this matter.
Despite several widespread arrests of drug traffickers and medically abused patients, the federal government has in most cases sanctioned the medical marijuana trade in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Agents of the Bureau of Drugs are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they will hardly close their eyes to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, according to Kevin A. Sabet.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the actions of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on opening new marijuana stores, which would not have been opened before a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month ban on the marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a position to give someone a license, and then it will cause serious problems at the federal level,” says Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our city voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still a lot of unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I was survived from Oxford for being a conservative.
Persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
As far as I can remember, I have always dreamed of enrolling in Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the world's best educational institution, a modern analogue of an ancient symposium laying the two foundations of civilization - freedom of thought and tolerance.
Yet, after two weeks of studying at the Faculty of History at Oxford University’s Wooster College in the late eighties, I packed up and left, which resulted in the first real scandal of my life.
My father couldn't stand it and cried.
Friends were misunderstood.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn’t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I had to leave because I had to drink from the crumbly cups.
It wasn't really that funny.
I ran away.
Yes, I escaped because I was systematically poisoned and intimidated.
Not at all because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I was in private school.
I was only poisoned for one reason, and in this glorious cradle of enlightenment it looked like true barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, now deceased Woodrow Wyatt, was a well-known adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the Conservatives.
You might ask, why do you think about it now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students who adhere to right-centered views are subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of conservative students in Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as those granted to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives from the Corpus Christi College Student Club in Cambridge say they are "often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks and made to feel unwanted guests" because of their political views.
They wish to introduce an additional representative to the College ' s Equal Rights Committee in order to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only exacerbated by a recently released BBC 2 documentary about politics in the student environment "The Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right", in which conservatives were presented by eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cook, a former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association who rides a rolls-crown, wears a silver suit and a cane with a silver cane.
In other universities, conservative students complain that they are making “goats of dismissal due to higher tuition fees.”
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, said in an interview with one of Sunday's newspapers that "in the university environment, the bias towards left-wing views is increasing.
People who don’t even know us, in advance, consider us ruthless and impunity-ridden children of wealthy parents.
Samuel Roberts, 21, a student at Corpus Christi College's historic faculty, who filed a request for protection, calls such an atmosphere "uncomfortable", and Stephanie Cheryl, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Association of Conservatives, said that the student's attitude towards the club's members was "uncomfortable".
“This poses a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and simply to the normal life of the club members,” she says.
The first few weeks in Oxford I was not just a minority, I was alone.
I entered there in September 1986, a shy and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford had a fever of hatred for the conservative party.
A year earlier, the university had voted to deprive former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree because of budget cuts to higher education.
In such an atmosphere, even Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
In the first days of the first week, when students get to know each other and the teachers, I felt for the first time what awaits me.
I had no idea that not only did the teachers look through their fingers at the torture of conservative students, but they also enjoyed participating in it.
Political issues – miners’ strike, privatization, and the government’s refusal to impose sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa – penetrated the walls of the auditoriums lined with wooden panels.
In my first seminar I had to translate the French text of the eighteenth century into English, and I was not ready for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the teacher, now deceased Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was hard for me, I stopped.
Harry Pitt was a very bile-like person with a face similar to a cake.
"Thatcherists don't basically teach French, or they just lack brains?" he asked.
Other students were cheeky.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I advise you to take a few initial lessons of French in your spare time, if you are not, of course, very busy spinning around in society," Pitt whispered.
I went back to my room completely unhappy.
That night in college, I sat alone for lunch; then someone slapped me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year student from the English language faculty, who presented himself as a member of the University’s Association of Conservatives.
"I know who you are," he said friendlyly.
- Unfortunately, the situation is as follows:
Anyone suspected of sympathy with the Conservatives will be harassed.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be harder for you.
Most conservative first-graders pretend to be Labourists.”
Later, at the local pub, I cowardly tried to hypocritize.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick failed.
A first-year student at the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contagious."
Other students took his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
“How do conservatives have sex?” one of them asked.
- They're biting each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the abolition of prosecution in the 1960s.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or will I have to meet like-minded people only under the cover of the night?
Will I be forced to become a Labour Party and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years have seemed like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who didn’t hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only because he belonged to the Conservatives, but also because he was Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of her speakers.
He hardly showed up in college.
He despised him for his provinciality, pettyness, and commitment to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he took a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to drive to Oxford from a parent’s home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased friends in the capital.
I told my father I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the 1940s, any political views were adopted there.
“It’s the best university in the world,” he said.
- They can't do that, except in the city of dormant spires...
Even my communist friends always behaved flawlessly.”
His wet eyes blurred.
“Don’t make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You'll break my heart if you leave the university."
I was exhausted by constant trips to London and my emotional defense was weakened.
My friend, also a conservative, could not withstand the pressure and abandoned his beliefs.
The next week during the seminar, when another history teacher called me “the enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Burning with shame, I confessed that "my parents were brainwashed" and called them "old fools."
The break was short.
The last nail in the lid of the grave of my career in Oxford was destined to smash my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns each week for Rupert Murdoch’s publications.
My door was locked.
I did not go out, and five minutes later my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and boarded the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a plax and a scumbag.
But at eighteen, no one should become the object of such anger and intimidation in the educational institution.
The saddest thing is that it was Oxford who not only released the fourteen prime ministers of the Tories, but still hides behind the undeserved reputation of the university, in which equality and freedom of thought are valued.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
About the exhibition "Valentino: Master of Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Tissen-Bornemica and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this at the opening of “Valentino: Master of Sewing”, a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high fashion dresses created by his “home” over the past 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "Il Signore" Garavani, but it could not have been written without his famous clients.
Valentino has always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of knowledge.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, will feature personal letters and photographs signed by the most eminent aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Santal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a modest porter from the city of Voghera in northern Italy to an idol of the international “elite”.
To be in love with the royal court - there is nothing wrong with that.
“They don’t at least extinguish the smoke of their cigarettes on your magnificent carpet, as some beautiful pop stars do,” says Baroness Fiona Tissen-Bornemitz.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an unparalleled host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
"We all really liked to come to his cottage in Gstaad," explains the ex-wife of Heini Tissen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Anelli or Evgenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to fame.
Despite this, he is a star.
Valeria Macca, representing Valentino
Argentinian model Valeria Macca recalls a charismatic fashion designer.
One day we went to dinner at his house, it was after a fashion show on the Plaza de España in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty invited were Sharon Stone and John Kennedy, the junior.
Valentino's style was manifested in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in its decor, in food, in music.
“Each of the guests made Valentino feel important and loved,” recalls the top model, whose work with the fashion designer began in 1995 during the Paris Fashion Week.
“He never goes out of fashion because his sketches are real works of art,” she concludes.
Parade of genealogy
The life of Garavani is not a story of obsessions, but of love with complete reciprocity.
He loves people with good education and high titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries of the Somerset house was turned into a glamorous podium of sixty meters in length, which offers a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of models and must defile on the podium, contemplating the "spectators" of the gems, which glitter with masterpieces of Valentino, such as s
In this audience of models shine such names as Sibylla of Luxembourg, Gloria von Turn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sofia Habsburg.
Nati Abascal and fashion designer, 2006
Many of these clients say that Valentino's first love is "impossible to forget."
I remember him very well.
These were trousers, a shirt, a "vest" and a jacket from the fall-winter 1971-1972 collection.
“It was a gift he gave me,” says Nati Abascal, one of the designer’s muses.
"I prefer him to the rest for his femininity, for his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty," the former Duchess of Feria added.
I really like the colors he uses: they have a lot of light and they “approach” his face.
The proportions are perfect.
Princess and fashion lawmaker Patricia della Jovampaola d'Arenberg can't forget the first time she dressed in Valentino either.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed that I would have the age and reason to wear one of his evening toilets.
The time finally came in the late 90s.
I bought my first dress from Valentino to wear it for a party at the castle of my cousin, Prince Edward de Lin.
It was a red dress, with a skirt with buckles, a corset in a fold and a neckline without straps.
"It was a dream that became a reality," says the widow of Rodrigo d'Arenberg.
“Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his passion is timeless,” explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess d'Arenberg keeps her festive dresses from the fashion designer with "maximum caution ... because the dress is not just a dress, it's also a collection of memories accompanying it."
The "King" of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Santal Miller's wedding dress for her wedding to Pavlos of Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the fashion designer calls his seams) to make this dress from ivory silk with an inlay of pearl, twelve kinds of different lace and a loop of four and a half meters.
According to journalist Susie Menkes, the highest authority of the specialized press, the dress represents a milestone in the high fashion of the end of the 20th century, "the return of customers from the upper world."
Stunned by the elite’s “lifestyle” for many years, Valentino is now his own best representative.
The Knight of the Great Cross (a mark of distinction of the highest rank in Italy), the Knight of Labor, Commander of the Order of Arts and Literacy, awarded with the Order of the Legion of Honor, Garavani collected as many honors as any of the spouses of his clients.
"My attention has always been drawn to his sophistication, his calmness, his neat and flawless appearance," recalls d'Arenberg.
The last time I saw him was a month ago at a gala dinner at the Orse Museum.
He was sitting at the table with Countess Jacqueline de Ribe, my great friend.
"He was impeccable, there is no time for him."
If that's what the princess says...
The world's heaviest profession: miners from Kawah-Idgen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk life and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano on steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who earn a living from sulphur mining in the Kavah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulfurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes when in contact with air.
He cut off huge pieces of sulfur, whose total weight can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, throws the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up on a rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, whose height is 2,386 meters, only 250 meters, but exhausted loaders take more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle step, difficult to maintain balance and carefully tapping the road so as not to fall back and fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step could cost them their lives, as happened with one tourist from France, who fell off the rocks of Kawah-Idgen a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah Ejina earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
On the top, they pave their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys from the circus and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the weights that the mining company placed a little above, at a height of 1,850 meters.
It is about PT Kandi Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has been exploiting this volcano since 1960 and, better yet, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to petrochemical production, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
“As the norm is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each run,” explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily transports.
He spends three hours on each of them and in the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems miserable for such an inhuman effort, it is three times more than he would have earned in the field.
“The miners’ wages are very high according to local standards, where coffee is collected by 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly earnings is two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the trucker, who previously worked as a quarryman on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town not far from the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as crushing as the sulphur: "I married her, the girl from the bay
Anto has asthma, he breathes hard, coughs constantly, and his eyes run down due to toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah-Ijen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, he coughs constantly, and his eyes faint because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French," he said in more than acceptable English.
Punished with life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or gatekeeper in a hotel, but instead he does the job of a mule.
For a dirty wooden hut with other wearers, it rises every day at two o’clock in the night, because the sulfur does not stop leaking at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, illuminating his way with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he himself bought for his money.
About 400 carriers pull baskets with grey on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur production to save costs and does not provide any equipment to bearers who work on their own account and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don’t even get part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photo fee, which, along with a 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) ticket, guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mule people.
