Hector "Hetty" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The avid basketball traveler Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this sport for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico remember as many basketball stories as Hector "Hetty" Reyes.
After all, before the brain bleed tied him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a small-tier player, senior basketball league player, commissioner and head of BSN with the Bayamon Cowboys and President.
“I have played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, as when I was president of BSN, director general of the National Team and president of the federation in the 1990s,” Reyes recalls during a visit to his home in Bayamon, where he lives with Isabel, his 50-year-old daughter.
“Basketball was my life.
Reyes does not exaggerate by making this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and souvenirs collected for his long journey, testify to this.
The Bayamon in the Heart
With the greatest emotion he keeps those who remember his way through the Cowboys, from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when it was 15 years of his performance as a co-agent or contract agent.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed most because I had the opportunity to be a part of eight Cowboy Championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or manager.
There were many years of joy, including five championships that took place between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincie's debut on BSN.
From that moment onwards, Cuco Ortiz, who was a great administrator, was in charge,” Reyes said.
I remember Jean Bartov, who was coming here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), telling me, "I have a very strong player for you, 6'7".
"Would you?"
And that was the start of Minci, one of the best players that Puerto Rico had.
Bartov then recommended sniper Raymond Gauss, who gained citizenship and became one of our best bombers.
I remember saying that if Mincie had brought the championship to Bayamon, Gauss would have helped to win another one.
I enjoyed the Cowboys Championship with Gauss, but already at a distance, because by 1988 I was already the head of the federation.
By that time, I preferred to enjoy his achievements and the achievements of Minci in the national team.
I remember winning for the first time in the United States during the Olympic Qualifying Tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we got the fourth place and it was supposed to be bronze, if not the Canadian referee who made us win the final game, Reyes said.
Is that team from the 1990 World Cup the best team you've ever seen?
She is among the best, as well as the one who won the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite was the one from the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won the gold and beat the U.S. national team, which was pretty similar to the one that won the bronze at our World Cup.
Not only did Minci, Gauss, Ramón Rivas, Fico Lopez and 'Piculina' (Ortis), but also the young (Javier) 'Tonito' Colon and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario 'Kihoto' Isle-of-the-Morales.
The team, which may not have been the best in terms of staffing, but brought us a gold medal and great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic Qualifying Tournament in Neuquen, Argentina.
With players such as Canito Nieves, Pablo Aliseo and young Rolando Hurruitner in exchange for players temporarily suspended for the disorder in the Pan American Mar del Plata Championship, we won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Piculin Ortis.
His performance in international tournaments is impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level like Piculin did.
And that’s not to mention his career in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's a very complicated question.
We had a very good youngster, including Julio Toro, Flora Melendez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armando Torres.
From a young age, I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider your main achievement in the federation?
Participation in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 1990s, BSN had up to 17 teams in the season.
What do you have left to do?
There were things that I wanted to implement, for example, the regionalization of smaller categories.
For example, that the boys from Ponse play only in their area and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Now the guys are traveling and playing too much, and that’s superfluous.
At least I see the fruits of mandatory certification and coursework for managers, officials and judges.
It's a pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all, I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Icabel, who has always been with me.
