Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, became world-famous for his lead role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the Dallas TV series, in which he portrayed a businessman without principles, evil and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role of oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new Dallas season, died Friday night from complications caused by cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., a Dallas-based production studio.
“Larry is back in his favorite hometown of Dallas again, playing the iconic role he liked the most,” his family said.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and sequel, was next to Hagman when he died at Dallas Hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to everyone who knew him.
He was creative, generous, cheerful, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original personality and lived a full life,” Grey said in a statement.
Hegman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and admitted to drinking for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in the liver and underwent a transplant.
